The whole process goes like this:\
\
\pard\tx200\tx280\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardeftab720\fi280\ri-2860\qj
\ls4\ilvl0\cf2 {\listtext	
\f2 \uc0\u9642 
\f0 	}you create a Pseudo Grid System (different margins, different widths, different alignments)\
{\listtext	
\f2 \uc0\u9642 
\f0 	}you differentiate blocks of content (whitespace + anything typography)\
{\listtext	
\f2 \uc0\u9642 
\f0 	}you pile them in PGS (block management)\
\pard\tx200\tx280\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardeftab720\fi280\qj
\cf2 \
Three easy steps. \
You try to use all elementary tools available: font-face, font-size, font-weight, font-style, margin, padding, line-height, color, background-color. \

\b Each type of content block can have its own properties
\b0 , depending on complexity of structure/hierarchy. But this doesn't mean you can do anything since you must find balance and harmony. Thus 
\b proportions/ratios are working altogether: "edit one, alter all"
\b0 . Block margins depend on line-height which depends on font-size which depends on block margins which depend on all other blocks. For example: \
if font-size = 1em;\
then line-height = 1.5 (it is a ratio and it may be the best for readability)\
then text-indent = 1.5em (so that we get a square at the beginning of each paragraph)\
or margin/padding top + bottom = 1.5em (line-break = line-height).\
then drop cap = 3em or 4.5em\
etc. \
Margins for the pseudo grid may be: 0.5em, 1em, 1.5em, 2em, central column, 2em, 1.5em, 1em, 0.5em.\
And so on and so forth. It's up to you to decide whether you want it very neutral and symmetric or ridiculous and asymmetric. \
\
